```
All three cognitive outcomes are approximately normally distributed and centered near 0 this makes sense because they are factor scores, which are standardized by construction. This confirms we can use linear models without needing to transform the outcome variables.

```{r age-distribution}
ggplot(df, aes(x = age_numeric)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 20, fill = "steelblue", color = "white") +
  labs(title = "Age Distribution", x = "Age", y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()
```
The age distribution spans roughly 35–90, which matches the study design (HCA/AABC recruited adults aged 35+). The spread is relatively even, meaning our models won't be dominated by one age group.

```{r blood-distributions}
blood_data |>
  select(glucose, cholesterol, hdl, friedewald_ldl, hba1c) |>
  pivot_longer(everything()) |>
  filter(!is.na(value)) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = value)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, fill = "steelblue", color = "white") +
